<br>
The highly radioactive underground facilities doing &quot;civilian&quot; things that could be turned into military applications in about 15 minutes.  They discovered a massive underground complex that was highly radioactively contaminated.<br>
<br>
Iraqi scientists said they were told to bury things in their backyards used in nuclear weapons research so that the program could be reconstituted later.<br>
<br>
It was just a matter of time.<br>
<br>
As for the war, there are many that are not primarily financially motivated.  Vietnam, Korea, WW2, and WW1 were not, imo, *primarily* financially motivated.  Sure, they had massive financial consequences, and the reasons some countries were in them were financial.<br>
<br>
Take Vietnam for example.  The real reason we were there is to fight against the spread of communism.  Vietnam was not a major economy.  We didn't even want the territory.  Either outcome of the war had little economic effect on us.<br>
<br>
I suppose you could make a strong argument for Germany entering WW2 for economic reasons.  They weren't the whole thing, but the economic conditions of the Weimar Republic certainly encouraged war.  Italy entering the war was more about Mussolini proving that he was important imo.<br>
<br>
Every war had economic consequences, I just don't think that economics were the primary motivating factor in all wars.<br>
<br>
