<br>
War should imo be used as a truly last option.  N Korea became very scared when Bush gave his famous &quot;axis of evil&quot; speech then invaded Iraq.  They became under the impression that they may be next when Bush started his war rhetoric vis-a-vis Iraq.  They then pushed the UN nuclear oversight personnel out, and immediately launched into a program of developing nuclear weapons as rapidly as possible.  Concurrent to this, they have repeatedly asked the US to sit down with them and officially sign non-aggression treaty.  The US has strongly opposed this, which has further increased the paranoia of an already dangerously paranoid country.<br>
<br>
The leadership of NK feels increasingly pushed into a corner and is striking out.  Again, as per the Iranian discussion with nuclear weapons, they understand that if they come into (many believe they already have at least 2) nuclear weapons the US will give them breathing room.  In other words will think long and hard before attacking them.<br>
<br>
Along the DMZ stands approximately 1,000,000+ troops (that's 9 times the force in Iraq atm).  Seoul is just 60 miles south of the DMZ.  Launching even a limited strike against NK at this time when they are already pushed into a corner would be absolutely disasterous.  For I am certain that the smallest of strikes would send NK into an absolute frenzy of all out war.  Resulting in 100,000s of deaths, economic destruction of South Korea and likely Japan (NK medium range weapons can easily reach Tokyo).  <br>
<br>
One should try the diplomatic approach more before playing the war cards with NK imo.<br>
